[[File:M. H. de Young Memorial Museum.jpg|thumb|The [[de Young Museum]], part of the Fine Arts Museums of San Francisco]]
[[File:California Palace of the Legion of Honor, 01.JPG|thumb|The [[Legion of Honor (museum)|Legion of Honor]], part of the Fine Arts Museums of San Francisco]]

The '''Fine Arts Museums of San Francisco''', comprising the [[de Young Museum]] in [[Golden Gate Park]] and the [[Legion of Honor (museum)|Legion of Honor]] in [[Lincoln Park (San Francisco)|Lincoln Park]], is the largest public arts institution in the city of [[San Francisco]]. The permanent collection of the Fine Arts Museums, with about 150,000 objects, is organized into nine areas, each with a [[curator]]ial staff.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}

Unlike most other major art museums, the Fine Arts Museums of San Francisco do not have a large [[financial endowment|endowment]] from which to draw. The museums operate on an annual budget funded by membership dues, ticket sales, donations (from [[philanthropy]] and [[grant (money)|grant]]s) and purchases in its stores.<ref>Geoffrey A. Fowler (August 4, 2011), [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424053111903341404576482200285214460# "Museum Invests in Crowd-Pleasers"], ''[[Wall Street Journal]]''</ref> They are run in a private-public partnership with the city of San Francisco, which owns the two museum buildings and covers about 23 percent of their operating expenses by providing security guards and paying insurance premiums. In 2016, the two museums drew a combined 1,402,000 visitors.<ref name="artnewspaper">{{cite news|url=https://www.museus.gov.br/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/20170406-CPAI-Ranking2016Pub-Comp-.pdf |title="Visitor Figures 2016" |page=14 |newspaper=[[The Art Newspaper]] Review |date=April 2017 |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>

In 2012, the Fine Arts Museums of San Francisco and the [[Louvre]] signed an agreement that provides for collaborative exhibitions and the sharing of art works. The agreement has a duration of five years. It creates a partnership to promote short- and long-term loans art works that allow the works to be seen in both cities, joint [[publication]]s, [[art conservation]] <!--NOTE: DELIBERATE internal link to a [[WP:redirect]] page  --> projects and educational programs.<ref>Allan Kozinn (November 15, 2012), [http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/11/15/louvre-and-san-francisco-museums-sign-pact/ "Louvre and San Francisco Museums Sign Pact"], ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>

[[Thomas_P._Campbell|Thomas P. Campbell]] became director of the Fine Arts Museums on Nov 1, 2018.

