'''Hutcheson Macaulay Posnett''' (c. 1855 – 1927<ref>{{cite web|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=EP19010720.2.68|title=The June Magazines|date=20 July 1901|publisher=Evening Post|accessdate=2009-07-30}}</ref>) was an [[Ireland|Irish]]-[[New Zealand]] lawyer and scholar who was a pioneer in the field of [[comparative literature]].<ref>[http://www.complit.org/about.html CLAI - Comparative Literature Association of Ireland]</ref>
He used the word 'Comparative Literature' first time in English form.{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}} From 1885 until 1890 Posnett held the Chair of Classics and English Literature at the [[University of Auckland]] although he also examined students in [[economics]].<ref>[http://www.calendar.auckland.ac.nz/about/history.html History of The University of Auckland]</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first = Blyth |last = Conrad |title = History of the Economics Department of the University of Auckland with some notes on the early academic teaching of economics in New Zealand |publisher = [[University of Auckland]] |year = 2006 |url = http://www.business.auckland.ac.nz/comwebContent/docs/C_Blyth.pdf |format = [[Portable Document Format|PDF]] |accessdate = 2008-12-30 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081015030001/http://www.business.auckland.ac.nz/comwebContent/docs/C_Blyth.pdf |archivedate = 15 October 2008 |df = dmy-all }} p. 9.</ref> His works include ''The Historical Method in Ethics, Jurisprudence, and Political Economy'' (1882) and ''The Ricardian Theory of Rent'' (1884), but he is most notable for the 1886 ''Comparative Literature'', "considered today by many scholars as the foundational work for the studies gathered under the same name during the following century".<ref>{{cite journal | first = Boldor | last = Alexandru | title = Perspectives on Comparative Literature | version = MA Thesis | publisher = [[Babeş-Bolyai University]] | year = 2003 | url = http://etd.lsu.edu/docs/available/etd-0408103-104408/unrestricted/Boldor_thesis.pdf | format = [[Portable Document Format|PDF]] | accessdate = 2008-12-30 }} p. 36.</ref> Informed by [[Herbert Spencer]] and [[Social Darwinism]] and published as part of an "International Scientific Series", it explained the history of literature as occurring contemporaneously with social evolution, from simple and communal to individual and complex. Posnett's work was also much influenced by [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe]]'s concept of ''[[Weltliteratur]]'' ("world literature"). At the time of its publication, the ''Saturday Review'' stated "We find very little interest in Mr. Posnett's 'Comparative Literature.' The arrangement seems by no means well ordered. Heaps of information (not always correct) are 'shot' (like rubbish) all over the place. &hellip; How remote all this is from the study of literature!"<ref>{{cite book|last=Kirk|first=John Foster|authorlink=John Foster Kirk|title=A Supplement to Allibone's Critical Dictionary of English Literature and British and American Authors|volume=2|year=1902|publisher=J. B. Lippincott Company|location=London|page=1246}}</ref>
Posnett died on 5 September 1927 in Kingstown, Ireland, with English probate being executed on 5 December of that same year.<ref>{{cite book|last=Principal Probate Registry|first=|title=Calendar of the Grants of Probate and Letters of Administration made in the Probate Registries of the High Court of Justice in England.|year=1927|page=688}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/FTJN-4MR|title=Ireland, Civil Registration Indexes, 1845-1958 (FamilySearch)|work=Hutcheson M Posnett, 1855; citing vol. 2, p. 458, General Registry, Custom House, Dublin, Ireland; FHL microfilm 101737|publisher=FamilySearch|accessdate=11 November 2012}}</ref>
