{{Infobox scientist | name = Ofer Bergman | image = Ofer_Bergman_portrait.jpg | image_size = 160 | alt = Ofer Bergman | alma_mater = | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = | known_for = | footnotes = | work_institution = | author_abbreviation_bot = | author_abbreviation_zoo = | prizes = | religion = }}
'''Ofer Bergman (עופר ברגמן)''' is a senior lecturer at the Department of Information Science, [[Bar-Ilan University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://is.biu.ac.il/en/bergman|title=Department of Information Science, Bar-Ilan Uni.|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=15 November 2017}}</ref>
==Publications== The book ''The Science of Managing Our Digital Stuff'' written by Bergman and [[Steve Whittaker]] was published by [[MIT Press]] in November 2016.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=The Science of Managing Our Digital Stuff|last=|first=|publisher=The MIT Press|year=November 2016|isbn=9780262035170|location=|pages=}}</ref> It reports on studies comparing the use of [[Directory (computing)|folders]] to store computer files with various alternatives.
The User-subjective approach suggests design principles that helped creating several novel design schemes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=January 15, 2008|title=The user-subjective approach to personal information management systems design: Evidence and implementations|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/asi.20738/abstract|journal=ASIS&T|volume=59|pages=235–246|via=}}</ref> Many of them have been deployed and positively evaluated.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=November 2015|title=Spotting the Latest Version of a File with Old'nGray|url=https://academic.oup.com/iwc/article-abstract/27/6/630/880802/Spotting-the-Latest-Version-of-a-File-with-Old?redirectedFrom=PDF|journal=Interacting with Computers|volume=27|pages=630–639|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=April 2009|title=It's not that important: demoting personal information of low subjective importance using GrayArea|url=https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1518745&dl=GUIDE&coll=GUIDE|journal=ACM|volume=|pages=269–278|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=June 14, 2011|title=You never call: Demoting unused contacts on mobile phones using DMTR|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00779-011-0411-3|journal=Personal and Ubiquitous Computing|volume=16|pages=757–766|via=SpringerLink}}</ref>
In a paper co-authored by Bergman and six other researchers, published in ''Scientific Reports'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Scientific Reports, Navigating through digital folders uses the same brain structures as real world navigation |url=http://www.nature.com/articles/srep14719}}</ref> the neurological bases for personal information retrieval are discussed. The study was mentioned in the ''[[Daily Mail]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Mail Online, Most humans use the same part of the brain as a dog looking for a bone when retrieving computer files |url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-3263763/Most-humans-use-brain-dog-looking-bone-retrieving-computer-files.html }}</ref> and The ''[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wall Street Journal, The Magic of Tidying Up—Digitally |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-magic-of-tidying-updigitally-1437338785}}</ref>
==Talks== Bergman took part in a PIM research community by initiating the first researchers meeting in 2004,<ref>{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=|year=2004|title=Personal information management|url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=986164|format=PDF|journal=CHI '04 Extended Abstracts on Human Factors in Computing System|publisher=ACM Digital Library|volume=|pages=1598–1599|doi=10.1145/985921.986164|accessdate=15 November 2017|via=}}</ref> a discussion group for researchers who participate in various workshops<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pim.ischool.washington.edu/participants.htm|title=The PIM Workshop An NSF-Sponsored Invitational Workshop on Personal Information Management|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=15 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pim2008.org/|title=Personal Information Management: PIM 2008|last=|first=|date=April 5{{ndash}}6, 2008|website=|location=CHI 2008 Workshop, Florence, Italy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090129132930/http://pim2008.org/|archivedate=January 29, 2009|deadurl=yes|accessdate=15 November 2017}}</ref> and panels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asis.org/Conferences/AM05/abstracts/51.html|title=Personal Information Management in the Present and Future Perfect: Reports from a Special NSF-Sponsored Workshop|author=William Jones & Harry Bruce|first=|date=October 28 {{ndash}} November 2, 2005|website=|location=Westin Charlotte, Charlotte, North Carolina|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=15 November 2017}}</ref>
