{{Infobox person | name = Victor Udwin | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Victor Morris Udwin | birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1953}} | birth_place = [[Bedford, England]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = American | other_names = | occupation = Author, Professor | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = ''Between Two Armies: The Place of the Duel in Epic Culture'' }} '''Victor Morris Udwin''' (born 1953) is an American author and professor of German and [[Comparative literature]] at the [[University of Tulsa]], where he has been teaching since 1990. He has written several publications including ''Between Two Armies: The Place of the Duel in Epic Culture'' in 1999,<ref>{{cite book|last=Udwin|first=Victor Morris|date=1999|title=Between Two Armies: The Place of the Duel in Epic Culture|publisher=E.J. Brill}}</ref> "Autopoiesis and Poetry" in ''Textuality and Subjectivity: Essays on Language and Being'',<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Timm|editor1-first=Eitel|date=1991|title=Textuality and Subjectivity: Essays on Language and Being|publisher=Camden House}}</ref> as well as writing several sections of ''The Nibelungen Tradition: An Encyclopedia'',<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Wunderlich|editor1-first=Werner|editor2-last=Mueller|editor2-first=Ulrich|editor3-last=Gentry|editor3-first=Frank|date=2000|title=The Nibelungen Tradition: An Encyclopedia|publisher=New York: Garland}}</ref> in addition to several other publications.
Born in England to South African parents, his family moved to South Africa when Udwin was three months old. His family then moved to the United States when Udwin was six years of age. After attending [[University of California, Irvine]] for two years, he transferred to [[University of California, Berkeley]]. He received his BA, MA, and PhD from UC Berkeley in 1976, 1980 and 1985, respectively.<ref name=udwin>http://www.personal.utulsa.edu/~victor-udwin/udwincv.pdf</ref>
==List of Publications<ref name=udwin/>== *''Between Two Armies: The Place of the Duel in Epic Culture'' (1999) *"Battle," "Conflict," "Destruction," "Duel," "Giant," "Numbers," "urliuge," "Heroic Age," "Oral Poetry," and "Traditional Narrative Material," in ''The Nibelungen Tradition: An Encyclopedia'' (2000) *"Autopoiesis and Poetry," in ''Textuality and Subjectivity: Essays on Language and Being'' (1991) *"Der materiale Signifikant," in ''Materialität der Kommunikation'' (1988) *"Reading the Red Ball—A Phenomenology of Narrative Processes," in ''Papers in Comparative Literature'' (1988): pages 115–26 *"Reading and Writing—the Rhetoric of Reversal," Reader 17 (1987): pages 5–16
